urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:0.226#The produce of annual labour supplies annual consumption,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:0.227#better or worse according to the proportion of produce to people,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:0.228#which proportion is regulated by the skill, etc., of the labour and the proportion of useful labourers,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:0.229#and more by the skill, etc., than by the proportion of useful labourers, as is shown by the greater produce of civilised societies.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:0.230#The causes of improvement and natural distribution are the subject of Book I.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:0.231#Capital stock, which regulates the proportion of useful labourers, is treated of in Book II.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:0.232#The circumstances which led Europe to encourage the industry of the towns and discourage agriculture are dealt with in Book III.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:0.233#The theories to which different policies have given rise are explained in Book IV.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:0.234#The expenditure, revenue and debts of the sovereign are treated of in Book V.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.1.235#Division of labour is the great cause of its increased powers,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.1.236#as may be better understood from a particular example,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.1.237#such as pin-making.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.1.238#The effect is similar in all trades and also in the division of employments.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.1.239#The advantage is due to three circumstances,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.1.240#(1) improved dexterity,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.1.241#(2) saving of time,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.1.242#and (3) application of machinery, invented by workmen,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.1.243#or by machine-makers and philosophers.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.1.244#Hence the universal opulence of a well-governed society,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.1.245#even the day-labourer's coat being the produce of a vast number of workmen.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.2.246#The division of labour arises from a propensity in human nature to exchange.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.2.247#This propensity is found in man alone.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.2.248#It is encouraged by self-interest and leads to division of labour,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.2.249#thus giving rise to differences of talent more important than the natural differences.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.2.250#and rendering those differences useful.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.3.251#Division of labour is limited by the extent of the power of exchanging.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.3.252#Various trades cannot be carried on except in towns.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.3.253#Water-carriage widens the market,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.3.254#and so the first improvements are on the sea-coast or navigable rivers,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.3.255#for example among the ancient nations on the Mediterranean coast.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.3.256#Improvements first took place in Egypt,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.3.257#Bengal and China;
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.3.258#while Africa, Tartary and Siberia, and also Bavaria, Austria and Hungary are backward.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.4.259#Division of labour being established, every man lives by exchanging.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.4.260#Difficulties of barterlead to the selection of one commodity as money,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.4.261#for example, cattle, salt, shells, cod, tobacco, sugar, leather and nails.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.4.262#Metals were eventually preferred because durable and divisible.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.4.263#Iron, copper, gold and silver,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.4.264#were at first used in unstamped bars,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.4.265#and after wards stamped to show quantity and fineness;
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.4.266#stamps to show fineness being introduced first,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.4.267#and coinage to show weight later.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.4.268#The names of coins originally expressed their weight.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.4.270#The next inquiry is what rules determine exchangeable value.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.4.271#Value may mean either value in use or value in exchange.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.4.272#Three questions,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.4.272#(1) wherein consists the real price of commodities, (2) what are the different parts of this price, (3) why the market price sometimes diverges from this price,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.4.276#will be answered in the next three chapters.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.5.277#Labour is the real measure of exchangeable value,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.5.278#and the first price paid for all things.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.5.279#Wealth is power of purchasing labour.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.5.280#But value is not commonly estimated by labour, because labour is difficult to measure.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.5.281#and commodities are more frequently exchanged for other commodities,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.5.282#especially money, which is therefore more frequently used in estimating value.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.5.283#But gold and silver vary in value, sometimes costing more and sometimes less labour, whereas equal labour always means equal sacrifice to the labourer,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.5.284#although the employer regards labour as varying in value.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.5.285#So regarded, labour has a real and a nominal price.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.5.286#The distinction between real and nominal is sometimes useful in practice,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.5.287#since the amount of metal in coins tends to diminish,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.5.288#and the value of gold and silver to fall.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.5.289#English rents reserved in money have fallen to a fourth since 1586,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.5.290#and similar Scotch and French rents almost to nothing.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.5.291#Corn rents are more stable than money rents,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.5.292#but liable to much larger annual variations,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.5.293#so that labour is the only universal standard.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.5.294#But in ordinary transactions money is sufficient,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.5.295#being perfectly accurate at the same time and place,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.5.296#and the only thing to be considered in transactions between distant places.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.5.297#So it is no wonder that money price has been more attended to.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.5.298#In this work corn prices will sometimes be used.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.5.299#Several metals have been coined, but only one is used as the standard, and that usually the one first used in commerce,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.5.300#as the Romans used copper,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.5.301#and modern European nations silver.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.5.302#The standard metal originally was the only legal tender,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.5.303#later the proportion between the values of the two metals is declared by law, and both are legal tender, the distinction between them ceasing to be of importance,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.5.304#except when a change is made in the regulated proportion.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.5.305#During the continuance of a regulated proportion, the value of the most precious metal regulates the value of the whole coinage, as in Great Britain,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.5.306#where the reformation of the gold coin has raised the value of the silver coin.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.5.310#Silver is rated below its value in England.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.5.311#Locke's explanation of the high price of silver bullion is wrong.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.5.312#If the silver coin were reformed, it would be melted.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.5.313#Silver ought to be rated higher and should not be legal tender for more than a guinea.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.5.314#If it were properly rated, silver bullion would fall below the mint price without any re-coinage.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.5.315#A seignorage would prevent melting and discourage exportation.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.5.316#Fluctuations in the market price of gold and silver are due to ordinary commercial causes, but steady divergence from mint price is due to the state of the coin.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.5.317#The price of goods is adjusted to the actual contents of the coinage.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.6.319#Quantity of labour is originally the only rule of value,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.6.320#allowance being made for superior hardship,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.6.321#and for uncommon dexterity and ingenuity.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.6.322#The whole produce then belongs to the labourer,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.6.323#but when stock is used, something must be given for the profits of the undertaker, and the value of work resolves itself into wages and profits.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.6.324#Profits are not merely wages of inspection and direction.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.6.325#The labourer shares with the employer, and labour alone no longer regulates value.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.6.326#When land has all become private property, rent constitutes a third component part of the price of most commodities.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.6.327#The real value of all three parts is measured by labour.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.6.328#In an improved society all three parts are generally present,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.6.329#for example, in corn,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.6.330#in flour or meal,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.6.331#and in flax.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.6.332#Rent is a smaller proportion in highly manufactured commodities.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.6.333#A few commodities have only two or even one of the three component parts.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.6.334#But all must have at least one,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.6.335#and the price of the whole annual produce resolves itself into wages, profits and rent,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.6.336#which are the only original kinds of revenue.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.6.337#They are sometimes confounded,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.6.338#for example, a gentleman farmer's rent is called profit,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.6.339#a common farmer's wages are called profit,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.6.340#and so are an independent manufacturer's wages,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.6.341#while the rent and profit of a gardener cultivating his own land are considered earnings of labour.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.6.342#A great part of the annual produce goes to the idle; the proportion regulates the increase or diminution of the produce.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.7.343#Ordinary or average rates of wages, profit,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.7.344#and rent
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.7.345#may be called natural rates,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.7.346#to pay which a commodity is sold at its natural price,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.7.347#or for what it really costs, which includes profit,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.7.348#since no one will go on selling without profit.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.7.349#Market price
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.7.350#is regulated by the quantity brought to market and the effectual demand.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.7.351#When the quantity brought falls short of the effectual demand, the market price rises above the natural;
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.7.352#when it exceeds the effectual demand the market price falls below the natural;
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.7.353#when it is just equal to the effectual demand the market and natural price coincide.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.7.354#It naturally suits itself to the effectual demand.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.7.355#When it exceeds that demand, some of the component parts of its price are below their natural rate;
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.7.356#when it falls short, some of the component parts are above their natural rate.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.7.357#Natural price is the central price to which actual prices gravitate.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.7.358#Industry suits itself to the effectual demand,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.7.359#but the quantity produced by a given amount of industry sometimes fluctuates.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.7.360#The fluctuations fall on wages and profit more than on rent,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.7.361#affecting them in different proportions according to the supply of commodities and labour.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.7.362#But market price may be kept above natural for a long time,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.7.363#in consequence of want of general knowledge of high profits,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.7.364#or in consequence of secrets in manufactures,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.7.365#which may operate for long periods,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.7.366#or in consequence of scarcity of peculiar soils,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.7.367#which may continue for ever.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.7.368#A monopoly has the same effect as a trade secret,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.7.369#the price of monopoly being the highest which can be got.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.7.370#Corporation privileges, etc., are enlarged monopolies.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.7.372#Market price is seldom long below natural price,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.7.373#though apprenticeship and corporation laws sometimes reduce wages much below the natural rate for a certain period
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.7.375#Natural price varies with the natural rate of wages, profit and rent.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.7.376#Wages will be dealt with in chapter viii.,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.7.377#profit in chapter ix.,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.7.378#differences of wages and profit in chapter x.,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.7.379#and rent in chapter xi.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.380#Produce is the natural wages of labour.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.381#Originally the whole belonged to the labourer.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.382#If this had continued, all things would have become cheaper,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.383#though in appearance many things might have become dearer.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.384#This state was ended by the appropriation of land and accumulation of stock,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.385#rent being the first deduction,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.386#and profit the second, both in agriculture,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.387#and other arts and manufactures.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.388#The independent workman gets profits as well as wages,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.389#but this case is infrequent.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.390#Wages depend on contract between masters and workmen.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.391#The masters have the advantage,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.392#though less is heard of masters' combinations than of workmen's.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.393#But masters cannot reduce wages below a certain rate,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.394#namely, subsistence for a man and something over for a family
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.395#Wages may be considerably above this rate,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.396#when there is an increasing demand for labourers,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.397#which is caused by an increase of the funds destined for the payment of wages. The funds consist of
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.398#surplus revenue,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.399#and surplus stock.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.400#The demand for labourers therefore increases with the increase of national wealth.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.401#High wages are occasioned by the increase, not by the actual greatness of national wealth.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.402#North America is more thriving than England.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.403#Wages are not high in a stationary country however rich.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.404#China is not going backwards and labourers there keep up their numbers.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.405#In a declining country this would not be the case.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.407#In Great Britain wages are above the lowest rate,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.408#since (1) there is a difference between winter and summer wages,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.409#(2) wages do not fluctuate with the price of provisions,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.410#(3) wages vary more from place to place than the price of provisions,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.411#and (4) frequently wages and the price of provisions vary in opposite directions, as grain is cheaper and wages are higher in England than in Scotland;
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.413#and in last century grain was dearer and wages were lower than in this;
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.414#while other necessaries and conveniencies have also become cheaper.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.415#High earnings of labour are an advantage to the society.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.416#Poverty does not prevent births
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.417#but is unfavourable to the rearing of children,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.418#and so restrains multiplication,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.419#while the liberal reward of labour encourages it,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.420#as the wear and tear of the free man must be paid for just like that of the slave, though not so extravagantly.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.421#High wages increase population.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.422#The progressive state is the best for the labouring poor
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.423#High wages encourage industry.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.424#The opinion that cheap years encourage idleness is erroneous.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.425#Wages are high in cheap years,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.426#and low in dear years,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.427#so that masters commend dear years.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.428#Messance shows that in some French manufactures more is produced in cheap years.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.429#No connexion is visible between dearness or cheapness of the years and the variations in Scotch linen and Yorkshire woollen manufactures
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.430#The produce depends on other circumstances, and more of it escapes being reckoned in cheap years
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.431#There is, however, a connexion between the price of labour and that of provisions.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.433#In years of plenty there is a greater demand for labour,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.434#and in years of scarcity a less demand,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.435#and the effect of variations in the price of provisions is thus counterbalanced.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.8.436#Increase of wages increases prices, but the cause of increased wages tends to diminish prices.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.9.437#Profits depend on increase and decrease of wealth,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.9.438#falling with the increase of wealth.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.9.439#The rate is difficult to ascertain,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.9.440#but may be inferred from the rate of interest,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.9.441#which has fallen in England,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.9.442#while wealth has been increasing.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.9.443#Profits are lower in towns, where there is much stock, than in the country, where there is little.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.9.444#Interest is higher in Scotland, a poor country, than in England.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.9.445#So too in France, a country probably less rich than England,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.9.446#but lower in Holland, which is richer than England.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.9.447#In the peculiar case of new colonies high wages and high profits go together, but profits gradually diminish.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.9.448#New territories and trades may raise profits even in a country advancing in riches.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.9.449#Diminution of capital stock raises profits.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.9.450#In a country as rich as it possibly could be, profits as well as wages would be very low,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.9.451#but there has never yet been any such country.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.9.452#Interest is raised by defective enforcement of contracts,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.9.453#and by prohibition.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.9.454#The lowest rate of profit must be more than enough to compensate losses,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.9.455#and so must the lowest rate of interest.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.9.456#In a country as rich as it possibly could be interest would be so low that only the wealthiest people could live on it.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.9.457#The highest rate of profit would eat up all rent and leave only wages.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.9.458#The proportion of interest to profit
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.9.458#rises and falls with the rate of profit.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.9.459#Countries with low profits can sell as cheap as those with low wages; and in reality high profits tend to raise prices more than high wages.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.461#Advantages and disadvantages tend to equality where there is perfect liberty.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.462#Actual differences of pecuniary wages and profits are due partly to counter-balancing circumstances and partly to want of perfect liberty
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.464#There are five counter-balancing circumstances:
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.465#(1) Wages vary with the agreeableness of the employment.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.466#Some very agreeable employments are exceedingly ill paid.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.467#The same thing is true of profits.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.468#(2) Wages vary with the cost of learning the business.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.471#The cost of apprenticeship accounts for the wages of manufacturers being higher than those of country labourers
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.472#Education for liberal professions is more costly and the pecuniary recompense consequently higher. Profits are not much affected by this circumstance.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.474#(3) Wages vary with constancy of employment.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.479#Constancy does not affect profits.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.480#(4) Wages vary with the trust to be reposed.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.483#Profits are unaffected by trust
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.484#(5) Wages vary with the probability of success.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.486#Law and similar professions are nevertheless crowded.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.487#Public admiration makes a part of the reward of superior abilities,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.488#except in the peculiar case of players, opera-singers, &amp;c.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.489#The greater part of men have an over-weening conceit of their abilities:
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.490#lotteries show that the chance of gain is over-valued,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.491#and the moderate profit of insurers shows that the chance of loss is undervalued.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.492#Young people are particularly prone to over-value the chance of gain and under-value the risk of loss.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.493#For this reason soldiers are poorly paid,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.494#and sailors not much better.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.495#Dangers which can be surmounted attract, though mere unwholesomeness repels.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.496#Profits vary with certainty of return.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.497#Profits are less unequal than wages, and their inequality is often only due to the inclusion of wages,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.498#as in the case of the profit of an apothecary,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.499#or country grocer.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.500#The greater difference between retail and wholesale profits in town than country is due to the same cause.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.501#The lesser rate of profit in towns yields larger fortunes, but these mostly arise from speculation.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.502#The five circumstances thus counter-balance differences of pecuniary gains,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.503#but three things are necessary as well as perfect freedom:
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.504#(1) the employments must be well known and long established,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.505#since new trades yield higher wages,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.506#and higher profits:
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.507#(2) the employments must be in their natural state,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.508#since the demand for labour in each employment varies from time to time
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.509#and profits fluctuate with the price of the commodity produced:
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.510#and (3) the employments must be the principal employment of those who occupy them, since people maintained by one employment will work cheap at another, like the Scotch cotters,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.513#Shetland knitters,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.514#Scotch linen spinners,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.515#and London lodging house keepers.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.516#The policy of Europe occasions more important inequalities
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.517#in three ways:
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.518#(1) It restricts competition in some employments,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.519#principally by giving exclusive privileges to corporations, which require long apprenticeship and limit the number of apprentices.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.522#Seven years is the usual period of apprenticeship.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.523#The Statute of Apprenticeship, which required it everywhere in England, has been confined to market towns,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.524#and to trades existing when it was passed.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.525#The term varies in France,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.526#and Scotland, where the regulations are less oppressive.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.527#All such regulations are as impertinent as oppressive.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.528#Long apprenticeships are no security against bad work,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.529#and do not form young people to industry
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.530#Apprenticeships were unknown to the ancients
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.531#Long apprenticeships are altogether unnecessary
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.532#Corporations were established to keep up prices and consequently wages and profit;
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.533#by means of which the towns gained at the expense of the country,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.534#being enabled to get the produce of a larger quantity of country labour in exchange for the produce of a smaller quantity of their own,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.535#as the exports of a town are the real price of its imports.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.536#That town industry is better paid is shown by the large fortunes made in it.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.537#Combination is easy to the inhabitants of a town,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.538#and difficult to those of the country, who are dispersed and not governed by the corporation spirit. No apprenticeship is prescribed for farming, though a difficult art,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.539#or for the inferior branches of country labour, which require more skill than most mechanic trades.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.540#The superiority of town industry is enhanced by other regulations, such as high duties on foreign manufactures.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.541#The superiority has declined in Great Britain.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.542#Meetings of people in the same trade ought not to be facilitated,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.543#as by registration of traders,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.544#by the establishment of funds for the sick, widows and orphans,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.545#or by incorporation.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.546#Corporations are unnecessary, and corrupt the workmen.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.548#(2) The policy of Europe increases competition in some trades.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.549#It cheapens the education of the clergy and thereby reduces their earnings;
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.550#so that it is only the great benefices, etc., which support the honour of the English and Roman Catholic Churches.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.551#The same cause, if present, would lower the reward of lawyers and physicians,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.552#as it has done that of men of letters,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.553#and that of teachers,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.554#who were much better paid in ancient times.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.555#Perhaps this cheapness of teaching is no disadvantage to the public.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.556#(3) The policy of Europe obstructs the free circulation of labour.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.557#Apprenticeship and corporation privileges obstruct circulation from employment to employment and from place to place.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.558#So that the changes of employment necessary to equalise wages are prevented.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.559#What obstructs the circulation of labour also obstructs that of stock.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.560#In England the circulation of labour is further obstructed by the poor law.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.561#Each parish was to support its own poor under 43 Eliz., c. 2,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.562#these were determined by 13 and 14 Car. II. to be such as had resided forty days, within which time, however, a new inhabitant might be removed.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.563#Notice in writing was required from the new inhabitant by 1 James II.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.564#Such notice was to be published in church under 3 W III.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.566#There were four other ways of gaining a settlement,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.567#two of which were impossible to all poor men,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.568#and the other two to all married men.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.569#and to all independent workmen
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.570#Certificates were invented to enable persons to reside in a parish without being immediately removable and without gaining a settlement.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.571#Certificates were required by the new parish but refused by the old.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.572#The courts declined to force overseers to give a certificate.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.573#This law is the cause of the very unequal price of labour in England,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.574#and an evident violation of natural liberty, though tamely submitted to
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.575#Wages were anciently rated by law or by justices of peace.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.576#London tailors' wages are still rated by law.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.577#Attempts were also made to regulate profits by fixing prices, and the assize of bread still remains.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.10.578#The inequalities of wages and profits are not much affected by the advancing or declining state of the society.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.579#Rent is the produce which is over what is necessary to pay the farmer ordinary profit.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.580#It is not merely interest on stock laid out in improvements,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.581#and is sometimes obtained for land incapable of improvement, such as rocks where kelp grows,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.582#and for the opportunity to fish.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.583#It is therefore a monopoly price
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.584#Whether particular parts of produce fetch a price sufficient to yield a rent depends on the demand.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.585#Some parts are always in sufficient demand: others sometimes are and sometimes are not.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.586#Wages and profit are causes of price; rent is an effect.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.587#The chapter is divided into three parts.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.588#Food can always purchase as much labour as it can maintain.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.589#Almost all land produces more than enough food to maintain the labour and pay the profits, and therefore yields rent.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.591#The rent varies with situation as well as with fertility.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.592#Good roads, etc., diminish differences of rent.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.593#Corn land yields a larger supply of food after maintaining labour than pasture.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.594#In early times meat is cheaper than bread,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.595#but later on it becomes dearer,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.596#and pasture yields as good a rent as corn land,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.597#and sometimes a greater one,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.598#as in the neighbourhood of a great town,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.599#or all over a populous country which imports corn,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.599#such as Holland and ancient Italy,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.600#and occasionally in a country where enclosure is unusual.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.601#Ordinarily the rent of corn land regulates that of pasture.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.602#Improved methods of feeding cattle lower meat in proportion to bread.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.603#The price of meat was higher at the beginning of the seventeenth century
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.604#than in 1763-4,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.607#whereas wheat was cheaper.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.610#The rent and profit of corn land and pasture regulate those of all other land.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.611#The apparently greater rent or profit of some other kinds is only interest on greater expense,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.612#as in hop, and fruit gardens,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.613#kitchen-gardens;
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.614#and vineyards.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.616#Land fitted for a particular produce may have a monopoly,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.617#such as that which produces wine of a particular flavour,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.619#or the West Indian sugar colonies,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.620#and in a less degree the tobacco plantations of Virginia and Maryland
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.621#So the rent of cultivated land producing food regulates that of most of the rest,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.622#and in Europe the rent of corn
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.623#If the common food was such as to produce a greater surplus, rent would be higher
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.624#for example, rice,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.626#or potatoes.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.628#Wheat is probably a better food than oats,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.628#but not than potatoes,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.629#Potatoes, however, are perishable.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.631#The materials of clothing and lodging, at first super-abundant, come in time to afford a rent
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.633#For example, hides and wool,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.634#stone and timber.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.635#Population depends on food:
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.636#so the demand for the materials of clothing and lodging is increased by greater case of obtaining food,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.637#which thus makes them afford rent.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.638#They do not, however, even then always afford rent:
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.639#for example, some coal-mines are too barren to afford rent,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.643#or too disadvantageously situated.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.644#The price of coal is kept down by that of wood,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.645#which varies with the state of agriculture
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.646#But in the coal countries coal is everywhere much below this price.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.648#The lowest possible price is that which only replaces stock with profits.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.649#Rent forms a smaller proportion of the price of coal than of that of most other rude produce.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.650#The situation of a metallic mine is less important than that of a coal mine,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.651#metals from all parts of the world being brought into competition
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.652#Rent has therefore a small share in the price of metals.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.653#Tin and lead mines pay a sixth in Cornwall and Scotland.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.654#The silver mines of Peru formerly paid a fifth,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.654#and now only a tenth,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.655#while profits are small
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.656#Mining is encouraged in Peru by the interest of the sovereign
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.657#The gold mines of Peru now pay only a twentieth in rent.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.658#The lowest price of the precious metals must replace stock with ordinary profits,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.659#but their highest price is determined by their scarcity.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.660#The demand for them arises from their utility and beauty:
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.660#and the merit of beauty is enhanced by their scarcity.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.661#The demand for precious stones arises altogether from their beauty enhanced by their scarcity.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.662#The rent of mines of precious metals and precious stones is in proportion to their relative and not to their absolute fertility.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.663#Abundant supplies would add little to the wealth of the world
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.664#But in estates above ground both produce and rent are regulated by absolute fertility.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.665#Abundance of food raises the value of other produce.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.666#The general course of progress is for produce other than food to become dearer,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.667#but there are interruptions,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.667#as in the case of silver,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.667#when new fertile mines are discovered.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.669#Silver would grow dearer in the general progress of improvement,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.670#but might grow cheaper if some accident increased the supply for many years together:
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.671#or remain stationary if demand and supply increased equally.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.672#These three things have happened during the last 400 years.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.673#From 1350 to 1570 silver gradually fell
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.674#In 1350 wheat was 4 oz. of silver per quarter,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.675#and was not less than that at the beginning of the century,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.678#and for some time before.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.680#From that it sank gradually to 2 oz. at the beginning of the sixteenth century and remained at that till 1570.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.685#The same fall has been observed in France.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.686#It may have been due to the increase of demand for silver or to a diminution of supply.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.687#Most writers, however, have supposed that the value of silver continually fell.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.688#They have been misled in their observations on the price of corn, (1) by confusing conversion prices with market prices;
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.690#(2) by the slovenly transcription of ancient statutes of assize;
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.693#or by misunderstandings of those statutes,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.695#and (3) by attributing too much importance to excessively low prices.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.696#The figures at the end of the chapter confirm this account.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.697#Sometimes the value of silver has been measured by the price of cattle, poultry, etc. But the low price of these things shows their cheapness, not the dearness of silver,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.698#for labour is the real measure.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.699#Cattle, poultry, etc., are produced by very different quantities of labour at different times,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.700#whereas corn scarcely varies at all,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.701#and also regulates the money price of labour.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.702#The authors were also misled by the notion that silver falls in value as its quantity increases.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.704#Increase of quantity arising from greater abundance of the mines is connected with diminution of value,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.705#but increase of quantity resulting from the increased wealth of a country is not
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.706#Gold and silver are dearer in a rich country,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.706#as may be shown by comparing China with Europe and Scotland with England as to the price of subsistence.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.708#Gold and silver are cheapest among the poorest nations.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.709#The fact that corn is dearer in towns is due to its dearness there, not to the cheapness of silver,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.710#and this is true also in Holland, Genoa, etc.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.711#So no increase of silver due to the increase of wealth could have reduced its value.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.712#No doubt exists as to the second period,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.713#silver sank, and a quarter of corn came to be worth 6 oz. or 8 oz. of silver.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.714#This was owing to the discovery of the abundant American mines.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.715#Wheat rose at Windsor market.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.717#The effect of the discovery of the American mines was complete about 1636.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.718#From 1637 to 1700 there was a very slight rise of wheat at Windsor,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.719#due to the civil war,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.720#the bounty on the exportation of corn,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.721#and the clipping and wearing of the coin,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.722#which was then much greater than in the present century.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.722#Moreover the bounty has been long enough in existence to produce any possible effect in lowering the price of corn.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.723#Silver has risen somewhat since the beginning of the century, and the rise began before,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.725#as is shown by Mr. King's calculations.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.728#A part from its effect in extending tillage, the bounty raises the price of corn, both in times of plenty and of scarcity.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.731#It is said to have extended tillage (and so to have reduced the price), but the rise of silver has not been peculiar to England.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.732#The alteration should be regarded as a rise of silver rather than a fall of corn.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.733#The recent high price of corn is merely the effect of unfavourable seasons.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.734#The bounty kept up the price between 1741 and 1750.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.735#The sudden change at 1750 was due to accidental variation of the seasons.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.736#The rise in the price of labour has been due to increase of demand for labour, not to a diminution in the value of silver.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.737#The decrease in the rent and profit of mines of gold and silver
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.739#has been stayed by the gradual enlargement of the market,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.741#(1) in Europe,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.742#(2) in America itself,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.743#and (3) in the East Indies,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.744#where the value of gold and silver was, and still is, higher than in Europe
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.745#The supply of silver must provide for waste as well as increase of plate and coin.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.746#Waste is considerable.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.747#Six millions of gold and silver are imported at Cadiz and Lisbon,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.748#as shown by Magens,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.749#Raynal,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.750#and other authors.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.751#This is not the whole of the annual supply, but by far the greater part.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.752#Brass and iron increase, but we do not expect them to fall in value. Why then gold and silver?
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.753#In consequence of their durability the metals, especially gold and silver, vary little in value from year to year.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.754#After the discovery of the American mines silver fell in proportion to gold
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.755#It is higher in the East
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.756#Magens seems to think the proportion of value should be the same as the proportion of quantity,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.757#but this is absurd
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.758#The whole of a cheap commodity is commonly worth more than the whole of a dear one, and this is the case with silver and gold.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.759#Gold is nearer its lowest possible price than silver.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.760#Diamonds are nearer still.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.761#It may be necessary to reduce still further the tax on silver in Spanish America.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.762#The greater cost of raising silver must lead to an increase of its price, or a reduction of the tax upon it, or both.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.763#The reduction of the tax in the past makes silver at least 10 per cent. lower than it would otherwise have been.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.764#Silver has probably risen somewhat in the present century.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.765#The annual consumption must at length equal the annual importation.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.766#and will then accommodate itself to changes in the importation.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.767#Gold and silver are supposed to be still falling because they are increasing in quantity and some sorts of rude produce are rising.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.768#It has already been shown that the increase of the metals need not diminish their value:
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.769#and the rise of cattle, etc., is due to a rise in their real price, not to a fall of silver.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.770#The real price of three sorts of rude produce rises in the progress of improvement:
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.771#(1) The sort which cannot be multiplied by human industry, such as game.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.772#(2) The sort which can be multiplied at will,  e.g.  cattle, poultry.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.773#When it becomes profitable to cultivate land to yield food for cattle, the price of cattle cannot go higher.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.774#It must go to this height in order to secure complete cultivation.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.775#Consequently new colonies are poorly cultivated.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.776#Cattle are the first of this second sort of rude produce to bring in the price necessary to secure cultivation,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.777#and venison is the last;
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.778#other things are intermediate,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.779#such as poultry,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.780#hogs,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.782#milk, butter and cheese.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.783#The rise of price, being necessary for good cultivation, should be regarded with satisfaction.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.784#It is due not to a fall of silver but to a rise in the real price of the produce.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.785#(3) The sort in regard to which the efficacy of industry is limited or uncertain,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.786# e.g.  wool and hides, which are appendages to other sorts of produce.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.787#Wool and hides in early times have a larger market open to them than butcher's-meat.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.790#In thinly inhabited countries the wool and hide are more valuable in proportion to the carcase.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.791#In the progress of improvement the wool and hide should rise, though not so much as the carcase
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.792#But in England wool has fallen since 1339.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.793#This has been caused by artificial regulations.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.794#The real price of hides at present is somewhat lower than in the fifteenth century,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.795#but their average price during the present century is probably higher.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.795#They are not so easily transported as wool,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.795#and tanners have not been so much favoured by legislation as clothiers
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.796#Regulations which sink the price of wool or hides in an improve country raise the price of meat,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.796#but not in an unimproved country.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.797#The Union sank the price of Scotch wool, while it raised the price of Scotch meat.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.798#The efficacy of industry in increasing wool and hides is both limited and uncertain.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.799#The same thing is true of fish, which naturally rise in the progress of improvement
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.800#The connexion of success in fishing with the state of improvement is uncertain.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.801#In increasing minerals the efficacy of industry is not limited but uncertain.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.802#The quantity of the precious metals in a country depends on its power of purchasing and the fertility of the mines.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.803#So far as it depends on the former circumstance the real price is likely to rise with improvement;
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.804#so far as it depends on the latter circumstance the real price will vary with the fertility of the mines,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.805#which has no connexion with the state of industry.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.806#The high value of the precious metals is no proof of poverty and barbarism,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.808#but the low price of cattle, poultry, game, &amp;c., is a proof of poverty or barbarism.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.809#A rise of price due entirely to degradation of silver would affect all goods equally, but corn has risen much less than other provisions,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.810#and has indeed been somewhat lower in 1701-64 than in 1637-1700,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.811#while its recent high price has been due only to bad seasons.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.813#The distinction between a rise of prices and a fall in the value of silver is not useless:
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.814#it affords an easy proof of the prosperity of the country,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.815#and may be of use in regulating the wages of the inferior servants of the state.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.816#The poor are more distressed by the artificial rise of some manufactures than by the natural rise of rude produce other than corn.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.817#But the natural effect of improvement is to diminish the price of manufactures.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.818#In a few manufactures the rise in the price of raw material counterbalances improvement in execution,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.819#but in other cases price falls considerably.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.820#Since 1600 this has been most remarkable in manufactures made of the coarser metals.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.821#Clothing has not fallen much in the same period,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.822#but very considerably since the fifteenth century.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.823#Fine cloth has fallen to less than one-third of its price in 1487,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.824#and coarse cloth has fallen to less than one half of its price in 1463.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.826#Hose have fallen very considerably since 1463,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.827#when they were made of common cloth.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.828#The machinery for making cloth has been much improved,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.829#which explains the fall of price.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.830#The coarse manufacture was a household one,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.830#but the fine was carried on in Flanders by people who subsisted on it, and was subject to customs duty,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.831#which explains why the coarse was in those times lower in proportion to the fine.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.832#Every improvement in the circumstances of society raises rent
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.833#Extension of improvement and cultivation raises it directly,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.834#and so does the rise in the price of cattle, &amp;c.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.835#Improvements which reduce the price of manufactures raise it indirectly,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.836#and so does every increase in the quantity of useful labour employed.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.837#The contrary circumstances lower rent.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.838#There are three parts of produce and three original orders of society.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.839#The interest of the proprietors of land is inseparably connected with the general interest of the society.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.840#So also is that of those who live by wages.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:1.11.841#but the interest of those who live by profit has not the same connexion with the general interest of the society.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.0.843#In the rude state of society stock is unnecessary.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.0.844#Division of labour makes it necessary.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.0.845#Accumulation of stock and division of labour advance together.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.0.846#Accumulation causes the same quantity of industry to produce more.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.0.848#This Book treats of the nature of stock, the effects of its accumulation, and its different employments.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.1.849#A man does not think of obtaining revenue from a small stock,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.1.850#but when he has more than enough for immediate consumption, he endeavours to derive a revenue from the rest,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.1.851#using it either as
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.1.852#(1) circulating capital,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.1.853#or (2) fixed capital.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.1.854#Different proportions of fixed and circulating capital are required in different trades.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.1.859#The stock of a society is divided in the same way into
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.1.860#(1) the portion reserved for immediate consumption,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.1.861#(2) the fixed capital, which consists of
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.1.862#( a ) useful machines,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.1.863#( b ) profitable buildings,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.1.864#( c ) improvements of land,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.1.865#and ( d ) acquired and useful abilities,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.1.866#and (3) the circulating capital, which consists of
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.1.867#( a ) the money,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.1.868#( b ) the stock of provisions in the possession of the sellers,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.1.869#( c ) the materials of clothes, furniture and buildings,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.1.870#and ( d ) completed work in the hands of the merchant or manufacturer.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.1.871#The last three parts of the circulating capital are regularly withdrawn from it.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.1.872#Every fixed capital is derived from and supported by a circulating capital,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.1.873#and cannot yield any revenue without it.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.1.874#The end of both fixed and circulating capital is to maintain and augment the other part of the stock.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.1.875#The circulating capital is kept up by the produce of land, mines, and fisheries,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.1.876#which require both fixed and circulating capitals to cultivate them,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.1.877#and, when their fertility is equal, yield produce proportionate to the capital employed
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.1.878#Where there is tolerable security all stock is employed in one or other of the three ways.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.1.879#But in countries where violence prevails much stock is buried and concealed.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.880#Prices are divided into three parts, wages, profits, and rent,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.881#and the whole annual produce is divided into the same three parts;
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.882#but we may distinguish between gross and net revenue.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.883#Gross rent is the whole sum paid by the farmer; net rent what is left free to the landlord.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.884#Gross revenue is the whole annual produce: net revenue what is left free after deducting the maintenance of fixed and circulating capital.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.885#The whole expence of maintaining the fixed capital must be excluded,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.886#since the only object of the fixed capital is to increase the productive powers of labour,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.886#and any cheapening or simplification is regarded as a good.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.887#The cost of maintaining the fixed capital is like the cost of repairs on an estate,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.888#but the expence of maintaining the last three parts of the circulating capital is not to be deducted,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.889#the circulating capital of the society being different in this respect from that of an individual
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.890#The maintenance of the money alone must be deducted.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.891#The money resembles the fixed capital, since
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.892#(1) the maintenance of the stock of money is part of the gross but not of the net revenue,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.893#and (2) the money itself forms no part of the net revenue.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.894#It only appears to do so from the ambiguity of language, sums of money being often used to indicate the goods purchaseable as well as the coins themselves.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.896#We must not add both together.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.897#If a man has a guinea a week he enjoys a guinea's worth of subsistence, &amp;c.,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.898#and his real revenue is that subsistence, &amp;c.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.899#The same is true of all the inhabitants of a country.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.901#The coins annually paid to an individual often equal his revenue, but the stock of coin in a society is never equal to its whole revenue.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.902#Money is therefore no part of the revenue of the society.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.903#(3) Every saving in the cost of maintaining the stock of money is an improvement.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.905#The substitution of paper for gold money is an improvement.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.906#Bank notes are the best sort of paper money.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.908#When a banker lends out 100,000 in notes and keeps in hand only 20,000 in gold and silver, 80,000 in gold and silver is spared from the circulation:
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.909#and if many bankers do the same, four-fifths of the gold and silver previously circulating may be sent abroad,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.910#and exchanged for goods.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.911#either to supply the consumption of another country, in which case the profit will be an addition to the net revenue of the country,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.912#or to supply home consumption (1) of luxuries, (2) of materials, tools and provisions wherewith industrious people are maintained and employed.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.914#If to supply luxuries, prodigality and consumption are increased, if to supply materials, &amp;c., a permanent fund for supporting consumption is provided.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.915#The greater part of the gold and silver sent abroad purchases materials, &amp;c.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.916#The quantity of industry which the circulating capital can employ is determined by the provisions, materials, and finished work, and not at all by the quantity of money.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.918#The substitution of paper for gold and silver increases the materials, tools, and maintenance at the expense of the gold and silver money.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.919#The quantity of money bears a small proportion to the whole produce, but a large one to that part destined to maintain industry.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.920#An operation of this kind has been carried out in Scotland with excellent effects.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.921#There was at the Union at least a million sterling of gold and silver money, and now there is not half a million.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.922#Notes are ordinarily issued by discounting bills,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.923#but the Scotch banks in vented the system of cash accounts,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.924#which enable them to issue notes readily,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.925#and make it possible for every merchant to carry on a greater trade than he otherwise could.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.926#The Scotch banks can of course discount bills when required.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.927#The whole of the paper money can never exceed the gold and silver which would have been required in its absence.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.928#The peculiar expenses of a bank are (1) the keeping and (2) the replenishing of a stock of money with which to repay notes.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.929#A bank which issues too much paper will much increase both the first
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.930#and the second expense.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.931#as may be shown by an example.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.932#Banks have sometimes not understood this,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.933# e.g.,  the Bank of England,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.934#and the Scotch banks.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.936#The excessive circulation was caused by overtrading
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.937#A bank ought not to advance more than the amount which merchants would otherwise have to keep by them in cash
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.938#This limit is observed when only real bills of exchange are discounted.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.939#Cash accounts should be carefully watched to secure the same end,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.940#as they were for a long time by the Scotch banks, which required frequent and regular operations,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.941#and thus (1) were able to judge of the circumstances of their debtors,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.942#and (2) were secured against issuing too much paper.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.943#Bankers' loans ought to be only for moderate periods of time.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.944#More than twenty-five years ago the proper amount of paper money had been reached in Scotland,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.944#but the traders were not content,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.944#and some of them resorted to drawing and redrawing,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.945#which shall be explained
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.946#Bills of exchange have extraordinary legal privileges.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.947#So two persons, one in London and one in Edinburgh, would draw bills on each other.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.948#Much money was raised in this expensive way.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.949#The bill on London would be discounted in Edinburgh, and the bill on Edinburgh discounted in London,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.949#and each was always replaced by another.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.950#The amount thus advanced by the banks was in excess of the limit laid down above, but this was not perceived at first.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.951#When the banks found it out they made difficulties about discounting,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.951#which alarmed and enraged the projectors,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.952#then the Ayr bank was established and advanced money very freely,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.952#but soon got into difficulties,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.952#and was obliged to stop in two years.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.953#Its action and failure increased the distress of projectors and the country generally,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.953#but relieved the other Scotch banks.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.955#Another plan would have been to raise money on the securities pledged by borrowers:
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.955#this would have been a losing business,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.956#and even if profitable would have been hurtful to the country.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.957#Law's scheme has been sufficiently explained by Du Verney and Du Tot
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.958#The bank of England was established in 1694,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.959#enlarged its stock in 1697
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.960#in 1708,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.961#in 1709 and 1710,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.962#in 1717, and later.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.963#The rate of interest received by it from the public has been reduced from 8 to 3 per cent. and its dividend has lately been 5 per cent.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.964#It acts as a great engine of state.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.965#The operations of banking turn dead stock into productive capital,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.965#but make its commerce and industry somewhat less secure
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.966#Precautions should be taken to prevent the greater part of the circulation being filled with paper.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.967#Circulation may be divided into that between dealers and that between dealers and consumers.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.968#The circulation of paper may be confined to the former by not allowing notes for small sums.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.969#The issue of such notes enables mean people to become bankers.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.970#None for less than 5 should be issued.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.971#This would secure the circulation of plenty of gold and silver,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.972#and would not prevent banks from giving sufficient assistance to traders.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.973#A law against small notes would be a violation of natural liberty necessary for the security of the society.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.974#Paper money payable on demand is equal to gold and silver,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.975#and does not raise prices;
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.976#but paper not repayable on demand would fall below gold and silver,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.977#as happened in Scotland during the prevalence of the Optional Clause,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.978#and must have happened in regard to the Yorkshire currencies when small sums were repayable in guineas.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.979#The North American paper currencies consisted of government notes repayable at a distant date,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.979#and depreciated the currency to a great degree.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.980#They were therefore justly prohibited.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.981#Pennsylvania was moderate in its issues, and its currency never went below the real par.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.982#The colonial paper was somewhat supported by being received in payment of taxes.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.983#A requirement that certain taxes should be paid in particular paper money might give that paper a certain value even if it was irredeemable.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.984#A paper currency depreciated below the value of the coin does not sink the value of gold and silver.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.2.985#The only restrictions on banking which are necessary are the prohibition of small bank notes and the requirement that all notes shall be repaid on demand.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.3.986#There are two sorts of labour, productive and unproductive
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.3.987#Many kinds of labour besides menial service are unproductive.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.3.988#The proportion of the produce employed in maintaining productive hands determines the next year's produce.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.3.989#Part of the produce replaces capital, part constitutes profit and rent.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.3.990#That which replaces capital employs none but productive hands,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.3.992#while unproductive hands and those who do not labour are supported by revenue.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.3.993#So the proportion of productive hands depends on the proportion between profit with rent and the part of produce which replaces capital.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.3.994#Rent anciently formed a larger proportion of the produce of agriculture than now.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.3.995#Profits were anciently a larger share of the produce of manufactures,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.3.996#so the proportion of produce required for replacing capital is greater than it was.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.3.997#The proportion between the funds determines whether the inhabitants of the country shall be industrious or idle.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.3.998#Increase or diminution of the capital of a country consequently increases or diminishes its annual produce.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.3.999#Capitals are increased by parsimony or saving.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.3.1003#What is saved is consumed by productive hands.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.3.1004#The frugal man establishes a perpetual fund for the employment of productive hands.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.3.1005#The prodigal perverts such funds to other uses.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.3.1006#Whether he spends on home or foreign commodities makes no difference.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.3.1007#If he had not spent there would have been just as much money in the country and the goods produced by productive hands as well
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.3.1008#Besides, when the annual produce diminishes, money will go abroad,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.3.1009#and on the other hand money will come in when the annual produce increases.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.3.1010#So even if the real wealth of a country consisted of its money, the prodigal would be a public enemy.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.3.1011#Injudicious employment of capital has the same effect as prodigality.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.3.1012#Frugality and prudence predominate.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.3.1013#Prodigality is more intermittent than the desire to better our condition.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.3.1014#Imprudent undertakings are small in number compared to prudent ones.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.3.1015#Public prodigality and imprudence are more to be feared than private,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.3.1016#but are counteracted by private frugality and prudence.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.3.1017#To increase the produce of a nation an increase of capital is necessary.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.3.1017#If, therefore, the produce has increased, we may be sure the capital has increased.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.3.1017#This has been the case of almost all nations in peaceable times.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.3.1018#England for example from 1660 to 1776,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.3.1019#or from 1558 to 1660,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.3.1020#though there was much public and private profusion, and many other disorders and misfortunes occurred.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.3.1021#Private frugality and prudence have silently counteracted these circumstances.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.3.1022#A part from increase or diminution of capital different kinds of expense may be distinguished.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.3.1023#An individual who spends on durable commodities will be richer than one who spends on perishable ones.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.3.1024#The same thing is true of a nation.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.3.1025#The former expense is easier to bring to an end,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.3.1026#and gives maintenance to more people.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.3.1027#It does not follow that it betokens a more generous spirit.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.4.1028#Stock lent at interest is a capital to the lender, but may or may not be so to the borrower.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.4.1029#Generally it is so to the borrower,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.4.1030#except in case of mortgages effected by country gentlemen.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.4.1031#Loans are made in money, but what the borrower wants and gets is goods.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.4.1032#So the quantity of stock which can be lent is determined by the value of that part of the produce which replaces such capital as the owner does not himself employ.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.4.1032#This may be much greater than the actual money employed.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.4.1033#The money is altogether different from what is actually assigned either as principal or interest.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.4.1034#The stock to be lent at interest naturally grows as the whole quantity of stock increases.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.4.1035#Interest falls as the quantity of stock to be lent increases,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.4.1035#because profits diminish as it becomes more difficult to find a profitable method of employing new capital.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.4.1036#The notion that it was the discovery of the West Indies which lowered interest has been refuted by Hume.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.4.1037#If 100 are now required to purchase what 50 would have purchased then, 10 must now be required to purchase what 5 would have purchased then.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.4.1038#An increase in the quantity of silver could only diminish its value.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.4.1038#Nominal wages would be greater, but real wages the same; profits would be the same nominally and really.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.4.1039#An increase in the goods annually circulated would cause a fall of profits and consequently of interest.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.4.1040#The prohibition of interest is wrong, and increases the evil of usury.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.4.1041#Where a maximum rate is fixed, this should be somewhat above the market rate on good security,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.4.1042#but not much above, or the greater part of loans would be to prodigals and projectors.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.4.1043#No law can reduce interest below the market rate.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.4.1044#The number of years' purchase commonly paid for land depends on the rate of interest.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.5.1045#The quantity of labour put in motion and the value added to the annual produce by capitals vary with their employment.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.5.1046#There are four different ways of employing capital,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.5.1047#all of which are necessary,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.5.1048#(1) procuring rude produce,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.5.1049#(2) manufacturing,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.5.1050#(3) transportation,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.5.1051#and (4) distribution.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.5.1052#The employers of such capitals are productive labourers
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.5.1053#the capital of the retailer employs only himself;
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.5.1054#the capital of the merchant employs sailors and carriers;
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.5.1055#the capital of the manufacturer employs his workmen;
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.5.1056#the capital of the farmer employs his servants and his cattle, and adds a much greater value to the annual produce than other capital.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.5.1057#Capitals employed in agriculture and retail trade must reside within the country,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.5.1058#the capital of the merchant may reside anywhere;
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.5.1059#the capital of the manufacturer must be where the manufacture is, but that is not necessarily determined.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.5.1060#Whether the merchant who exports belongs to the country or not makes little difference.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.5.1061#The capital of the manufacturer will put into motion more native labour if it resides within the country, but may be useful even if outside it.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.5.1062#Particular countries often have not enough capital for cultivation, manufactures, and transportation
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.5.1063#In such cases the larger the proportion employed in agriculture, the larger will be the annual produce.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.5.1064#The quickest way to make the capital sufficient for all these purposes is to begin with the most profitable.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.5.1065#That they have done so is the principal cause of the progress of the American colonies.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.5.1066#Great countries have scarcely ever acquired sufficient capital for all those purposes.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.5.1067#Different kinds of wholesale trade employ different quantities of productive labour and add different amounts to the annual produce.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.5.1068#There are three different kinds of trade home, foreign and carrying.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.5.1069#Capital employed in buying in one part of the country to sell in another replaces two domestic capitals.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.5.1070#Capital employed in importation replaces one domestic and one foreign capital.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.5.1071#Its returns are not so quick as those of home trade.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.5.1072#Roundabout foreign trade has the same effect as direct.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.5.1073#Foreign trade carried on by means of gold and silver is in no way different from the rest.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.5.1074#Capital employed in the carrying trade replaces two foreign capitals.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.5.1074#It may employ ships and sailors belonging to the country, but this is not always the case,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.5.1074#and equal capital employed in importation or coasting trade may employ as many ships and men.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.5.1075#Capital in home trade therefore supports more productive labour than capital employed in foreign trade, which, however, supports more than capital in the carrying trade Political economy ought consequently not to allure capital into the foreign or the carrying trade,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.5.1076#though each is advantageous when naturally introduced.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.5.1077#The surplus of the produce of particular branches of industry must be sent abroad.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.5.1078#Foreign goods obtained in exchange must often be reexported.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.5.1079#When the other employments are full, the surplus capital disgorges itself into the carrying trade, which is a symptom rather than a cause of great national wealth.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.5.1080#The possible extent of the carrying trade is much the greatest.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.5.1081#Agriculture does not yield sufficient profit to attract all the capital which it might absorb.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:2.5.1081#The reason will be explained in the next two books.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.1.1082#The great commerce is that between town and country, which is obviously advantageous to both.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.1.1083#The cultivation of the country must be prior to the increase of the town,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.1.1083#though the town may sometimes be distant from the country from which it derives its subsistence.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.1.1084#This order of things is favoured by the natural preference of man for agriculture.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.1.1085#Cultivators require the assistance of artificers, who settle together and form a village, and their employment augments with the improvement of the country.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.1.1086#In the American colonies an artificer who has acquired sufficient stock becomes a planter instead of manufacturing for distant sale,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.1.1087#as in countries where no uncultivated land can be procured.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.1.1088#Manufactures are naturally preferred to foreign commerce.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.1.1089#So the natural course of things is first agriculture, then manufactures, and finally foreign commerce.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.1.1090#But this order has been in many respects inverted.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.2.1091#After the fall of the Roman Empire all the land of Western Europe was engrossed, chiefly by large proprietors.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.2.1092#Primogeniture and entails prevented the great estates being divided.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.2.1093#Primogeniture was introduced because every great landlord was a petty prince.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.2.1094#It is now unreasonable, but supports the pride of family distinctions.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.2.1095#Entails have the same origin,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.2.1096#and are now absurd.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.2.1097#Great proprietors are seldom great improvers.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.2.1098#The occupiers were not likely to improve, as they were slaves attached to the land and incapable of acquiring property.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.2.1099#Slave labour is the dearest of all.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.2.1100#At present sugar and tobacco can afford slave cultivation, corn cannot.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.2.1101#The slaves were succeeded by metayers,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.2.1102#who are very different in that they can acquire property.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.2.1103#But they could have no interest to employ stock in improvement.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.2.1104#Metayers were followed by farmers, who sometimes find it to their interest to improve when they have a lease, but leases were long insecure.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.2.1104#The forty-shilling freeholder vote in England contributes to the security of the farmer.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.2.1105#The law of Scotland is not quite so favourable.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.2.1106#In the rest of Europe the farmer is less secure.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.2.1107#Customary services were vexatious to the farmer,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.2.1108#and so also were compulsory labour on the roads,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.2.1108#purveyance
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.2.1109#and tallages.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.2.1110#Even under the best laws the farmer is at a disadvantage in improving,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.2.1110#but large farmers are the principal improvers after small proprietors.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.2.1111#The common prohibition of the export of corn and the restraints on internal trade in agricultural produce were further discouragements to agriculture.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.3.1112#The townsmen were not at first favoured more than the countrymen.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.3.1113#They were very nearly of servile condition,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.3.1114#but arrived at liberty much earlier than the country people, acquiring the farm of their town,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.3.1115#first for a term of years and afterwards in perpetuity,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.3.1116#as well as other privileges equivalent to freedom,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.3.1117#and a government of their own.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.3.1118#It seems strange that sovereigns should have abandoned the prospect of increased revenue and have erected independent republics,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.3.1119#but the towns were the natural allies of the sovereign against the lords.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.3.1120#The sovereigns who quarrelled most with the barons were the most liberal to the towns.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.3.1121#The city militia was often able to overpower the neighbouring lords, as in Italy and Switzerland.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.3.1122#In France and England the cities could not be taxed without their own consent.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.3.1123#In consequence of this greater security of the towns industry flourished and stock accumulated there earlier than in the country.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.3.1124#Cities on the sea-coast or on navigable rivers are not dependent on the neighbouring country
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.3.1125#The cities of Italy were the first to grow opulent, being centrally situated and benefited by the crusades.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.3.1126#The cities imported manufactures and luxuries from richer countries, which were paid for by rude produce.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.3.1127#Demand for such manufactured articles having become considerable, their manufacture was established in the cities.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.3.1128#All countries have some manufactures.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.3.1130#Sometimes manufactures for distant sale are introduced in imitation of foreign manufactures.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.3.1131#Sometimes they have grown up out of the coarser home manufactures.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.4.1132#The rise of towns benefited the country,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.4.1133#because they afforded (1) already market for its produce,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.4.1134#(2) because merchants bought land in the country and improved it,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.4.1135#and (3) because order and good government were introduced.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.4.1136#Before foreign commerce and fine manufactures are introduced great proprietors are surrounded by bands of retainers,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.4.1137#and tenants at will were just as dependent as retainers.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.4.1138#The power of the ancient barons was founded on this.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.4.1139#It was anterior to and independent of the feudal law.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.4.1140#It was moderated by the feudal law,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.4.1141#and undermined by foreign commerce.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.4.1142#At present a rich man maintains in all as many persons as an ancient baron, but he contributes only a small portion of the maintenance of each person.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.4.1144#To meet their new expenses the great proprietors dismissed their retainers and their unnecessary tenants, and gave the remaining tenants long leases,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.4.1145#thus making them independent.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.4.1146#The great proprietors thus became insignificant.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.4.1147#Old families are rare in commercial countries.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.4.1148#A revolution was thus insensibly brought about,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.4.1149#and commerce and manufactures became the cause of the improvement of the country.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.4.1150#This order of things is both slow and uncertain compared with the natural order, as may be shown by the rapid progress of the North American colonies,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.4.1151#and the slow progress of England in agriculture in spite of favours accorded to it
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.4.1152#and the still slower progress of France,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.4.1153#Spain and Portugal.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.4.1154#Italy alone was improved throughout by foreign commerce and exported manufactures.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:3.4.1155#The national capital acquired by commerce and manufactures is an uncertain possession till realised in the improvement of land
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.0.1156#The first object of political economy is to provide subsistence for the people
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.0.1157#Two different systems proposed for this end will be explained.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.1.1158#Wealth and money in common language are considered synonymous.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.1.1159#Similarly the Tartars thought wealth consisted of cattle.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.1.1160#Locke thought gold and silver the most substantial part of the wealth of a nation. 
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.1.1161#Others say that it is necessary to have much money in order to maintain fleets and armies abroad.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.1.1162#So all European nations have tried to accumulate gold and silver.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.1.1162#At first by a prohibition of exportation,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.1.1163#but merchants found this inconvenient,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.1.1164#and therefore argued that exportation did not always diminish the stock in the country,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.1.1165#and that the metals could be retained only by attention to the balance of trade.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.1.1166#Their arguments were partly sophistical,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.1.1167#but they convinced parliaments and councils.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.1.1167#The exportation of foreign coin and bullion was permitted by France and England, and the exportation of Dutch coin by Holland.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.1.1167#That treasure was obtained by foreign trade became a received maxim.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.1.1168#Gold and silver will be imported without any attention of government,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.1.1169#They can be imported more easily than other commodities when there is an effectual demand.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.1.1170#When their quantity exceeds the demand it is impossible to prevent their exportation,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.1.1170#and it would be equally impossible to prevent their importation if the supply fell short of the effectual demand.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.1.1171#It is this ease of transportation which makes the value of gold and silver so uniform.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.1.1172#If they did fall short, their place could be supplied by paper.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.1.1173#The common complaint of scarcity of money only means difficulty in borrowing.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.1.1174#Money makes but a small part of the national capital.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.1.1175#It is easier to buy than to sell simply because money is the instrument of commerce.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.1.1176#The durability of a commodity is no reason for accumulating more of it than is wanted.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.1.1177#Accumulation of gold and silver is not necessary for carrying on distant wars,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.1.1178#which may be paid for by exporting: (1) gold and silver, (2) manufactures, or (3) rude produce
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.1.1179#The gold and silver consists of money in circulation, plate, and money in the treasury.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.1.1180#Little can be spared from the money in circulation;
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.1.1181#plate has never yielded much;
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.1.1182#accumulation in the treasury has been abandoned.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.1.1183#The foreign wars of the century have evidently not been paid for from the money in circulation,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.1.1184#but by commodities.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.1.1185#Part of the bullion which circulates from country to country may have been employed, but it must have been purchased with commodities.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.1.1186#The finer manufactures are the most convenient commodities for the purpose.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.1.1187#Rude produce is inconvenient.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.1.1188#The principal benefit of foreign trade is not the importation of gold and silver, but the carrying out of surplus produce for which there is no demand and bringing back something for which there is.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.1.1189#The discovery of America has benefited Europe not by the cheapening of gold and silver,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.1.1189#but by opening up of a new market which improved the productive powers of labour.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.1.1190#The discovery of the sea passage to the East Indies would have been still more advantageous if the trade to the East Indies had been free.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.1.1190#The exportation of silver to the East Indies is not harmful.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.1.1191#Writers who begin by including lands, houses and consumable goods in wealth often forget them later.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.1.1192#Wealth being supposed to consist in gold and silver, political economy endeavoured to diminish imports and encourage exports,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.1.1194#by restraints upon importation
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.1.1197#and encouragements to exportation,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.1.1202#which restraints and encouragements will be considered in the next six chapters.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.2.1203#High duties and prohibitions giving a monopoly to a particular home industry are very common.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.2.1204#They encourage the particular industry, but neither increase general industry nor give it the best direction.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.2.1205#The number of persons employed cannot exceed a certain proportion to the capital of the society,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.2.1206#and every man's interest leads him to seek that employment of capital which is most advantageous to the society.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.2.1207#(1) He tries to employ it as near home as possible
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.2.1209#(2) He endeavours to produce the greatest possible value.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.2.1212#He can judge of this much better than the statesman.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.2.1213#High duties and prohibitions direct people to employ capital in producing at home what they could buy cheaper from abroad
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.2.1214#It is as foolish for a nation as for an individual to make what can be bought cheaper.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.2.1215#Sometimes by such regulations a manufacture may be established earlier than it would otherwise have been, but this would make capital accumulate slower,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.2.1216#and the country might always be just as rich if it never acquired the manufacture.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.2.1217#No one proposes that a country should strive against great natural advantages, but it is also absuid to strive against smaller advantages whether natural or acquired.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.2.1218#Merchants and manufacturers get the most benefit from high duties and prohibitions.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.2.1219#The free importation of foreign cattle would make no great difference to British graziers.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.2.1220#It might even benefit the cultivated plains at the expense of the rugged mountainous districts.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.2.1221#The free importation of salt provisions also would make little difference to the graziers,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.2.1222#and even the free importation of corn would not much affect the farmers.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.2.1223#Country gentlemen and farmers are less subject to the spirit of monopoly than merchants and manufacturers.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.2.1224#The prohibition of foreign corn and cattle restraints the population.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.2.1225#There are two cases which are exceptional,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.2.1226#(1) when a particular industry is necessary for the defence of the country, like shipping, which is properly encouraged by the act of navigation,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.2.1231#a wise act, though dictated by animosity,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.2.1232#and unfavourable to foreign commerce;
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.2.1233#and (2) when there is a tax on the produce of the like home manufacture.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.2.1234#Some people say that this principle justifies a general imposition of duties on imports to counterbalance taxes levied at home on necessaries,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.2.1235#but there is a difference,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.2.1236#since ( a ) the effect of taxes on necessaries cannot be exactly known,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.2.1237#and ( b ) taxes on necessaries are like poor soil or bad climate: they cannot justify an attempt to give capital an unnatural direction.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.2.1238#Taxes on necessaries are commonest in the richest countries because no others could support them
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.2.1239#There are two other possible exceptions to the general principle
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.2.1240#(1) Retaliation
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.2.1241#may be good policy where it is likely to secure the abolition of foreign restraints.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.2.1242#(2) It may be desirable to introduce freedom of trade by slow gradations.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.2.1242#But the disorder occasioned by its sudden introduction would be less than is supposed since
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.2.1243#( a ) no manufacture which is now exported would be affected;
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.2.1244#( b ) the people thrown out of one employment would easily find another,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.2.1244#especially if the privileges of corporations and the law of settlement were abolished.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.2.1245#Private interests are too strong to allow of the restoration of freedom of trade in Great Britain.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.2.1246#The fact that equitable regard is due to the manufacturer who has fixed capital in his business is an argument against the establishment of new monopolies.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.2.1247#Customs duties imposed for revenue remain to be considered hereafter
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.3.1248#British restraints on imports from France are an example.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.3.1248#Such restraints are unreasonable on the principles of the mercantile system, since
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.3.1249#(1) if free trade with France did lead to an unfavourable balance with France, it might yet not do so with the world in general,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.3.1250#(2) a part of French imports might be re-exported and bring back gold and silver,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.3.1251#and (3) the balance cannot be certainly known:
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.3.1251#custom-house books are useless,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.3.1252#and the course of exchange is little better.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.3.1253#A favourable exchange with a particular country does not prove a favourable balance with that country.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.3.1254#Besides, the ordinary computation of exchange is often misleading, since
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.3.1256#(1) money is often below its nominal standard,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.3.1257#(2) coin is sometimes raised by seignorage above the value of the bullion contained in it,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.3.1258#and (3) bank money bears an agio.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.3.1259#Small states must admit foreign coin, which is of uncertain value.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.3.1260#Banks are then established to pay in standard money regardless of the condition of the coin, and this money bears an agio.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.3.1261#Before 1609 the common currency of Amsterdam was 9 per cent. below the standard.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.3.1262#The bank was then established to receive and pay coin at its intrinsic value in good standard money.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.3.1263#Money in the bank was not only up to the standard, but also secure and easily transferred, so that it bore an agio.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.3.1264#The bank receives bullion as well as coin, giving in exchange a credit in bank money to 95 per cent of the value.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.3.1264#It also gives a receipt which entitles the bearer to recover the bullion on repaying the sum advanced and paying  per cent. for silver and  per cent. for gold.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.3.1265#The receipts are generally worth something, and are renewed at the end of each six months.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.3.1266#The depositor usually parts with his receipt.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.3.1267#The bank money and the receipt together equal in value the bullion deposited.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.3.1268#Receipts for current coin are also given, but these are often of no value and are allowed to expire.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.3.1269#So there is a considerable sum of bank money for which the receipts have expired, but it is not a large proportion of the whole.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.3.1270#This cannot be drawn out of the bank.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.3.1271#So that if all the holders of bank money desired to exchange it for coin and bullion receipts might command an exorbitant price.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.3.1272#Of late years the bank has always sold bank money at 5 per cent. agio and bought at 4 per cent.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.3.1273#It professes to lend out no part of the deposits.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.3.1274#The amount of treasure in the bank is a subject of conjecture.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.3.1275#The city derives a considerable revenue from the various profits of the bank.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.3.1277#The whole doctrine of the balance of trade is absurd.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.3.1279#Where there is an even balance and the exchange consists wholly of native commodities two countries trading will gain nearly equally.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.3.1280#If one exported nothing but native commodities, and the other nothing but foreign, both would gain, but the first would gain most.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.3.1281#Mixed cases conform to the principle.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.3.1282#It would be no worse for England to pay in gold and silver than in tobacco.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.3.1283#The arguments against the French wine trade are fallacious.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.3.1283#The sneaking arts of underling tradesmen have been erected into political maxims and commerce has become a source of discord instead of unity.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.3.1285#The sophistry of merchants inspired by the spirit of monopoly has confounded the common-sense of mankind.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.3.1286#Wealthy neighbours are an advantage to a nation as well as an individual.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.3.1287#The French trade, if not restrained, would be much more advantageous to Great Britain than the American.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.3.1288#But the traders of France and England are jealous of each other.
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.3.1289#No country has ever been impoverished by an unfavourable balance, and those which have the freest trade have been the most enriched by foreign trade
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.3.1290#Prosperity and decay depend on the balance of produce and consumption,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.3.1291#which is quite different from the balance of trade,
urn:cts:fufolio:adamsmith.won.fu2018.heads:4.3.1292#and may be constantly in favour of a nation when the balance of trade is against it.
